  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is generally considered a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legitimate (i.e., \"clean\") by disguising the true origin of the funds. This is typically done through a series of complex transactions or financial maneuvers.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is prohibited under federal law, primarily through the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). Penalties for money laundering can be severe and may include:\n\n- **Fines**: Significant monetary penalties, often in the hundreds of thousands or millions of dollars.\n- **Imprisonment**: Sentences can range from several years to up to 20 years per count, depending on the specifics of the case.\n- **Additional penalties**: Forfeiture of assets involved in the laundering scheme and other civil or criminal penalties.\n\nMoney laundering is also criminalized under state laws and international agreements, and penalties can vary depending on the jurisdiction and the severity of the offense. \n\nIf you or someone you know is facing allegations of money laundering, it is crucial to seek legal counsel from an experienced attorney to understand the specific charges and potential defenses.",
